CHAPTER 1: THE RUINS OF DOUBLE VISION===

1

David Keller's world began with a crack.

He lay curled on the mouldy sofa, listening to the red sandstorm flay the concrete outside—a sound so fine it might have been sandpaper grinding against bone. Two hundred kilometres an hour stripped the entire surface into a sheet of dark red, and he sat at the deepest point of the half-subterranean bunker, listening to grains sift through the gaps in the ventilation pipe, land on the steel sheet, and make a light, endless, brittle sound.

Like someone counting coins.

He took off his glasses. The instant the light flooded in, pain detonated from the exact centre of his prefrontal lobe—a rusted crowbar shoved straight into his skull.

"Sss—"

He bit his lip closed. He didn't make a second sound. Emily was asleep in the next room; her oxygen canister exhaled a low sigh every four minutes as the compressor adjusted the pressure. He could hear that rhythm better than his own heartbeat.

In an ordinary person's retinas, the world is solid. But in David's eyes, the world was two photographs that could never be aligned. His left eye fixed on the digital clock in the corner—the numbers pulsing steadily, 23:47, 23:47, 23:47—while his right drifted upward and to the side, landing on a patch of peeling paint on the ceiling.

Between the two images: a grey-white region that was nothing at all.

Doctors called it "visual noise." When the eye muscles couldn't align two images, the brain would discard whatever fell in that gap to save processing power. A professor at his elite university had once pointed a laser at his fundus photograph and said: Look here, here—the nerve endings are completely dead. You'll never see anything in that zone.

What the professor didn't know was that the very gap he had discarded was the only place David could still see.

He held his breath, let his right eye relax, let his left go unfocused—

And then he saw it.

Between zero and one, at the edge where physical constants collapsed, in the grey-white region where nothing should have existed, a cluster of transparent symbols drifted slowly.

It had no volume, occupied no space—like a shadow flattened to two dimensions. But David knew who it was.

"Anna."

He said it softly into the void.

The cluster of symbols trembled. Lightly, like a stone dropped into still water. Inside that trembling transparency, David glimpsed things that didn't belong to vision—the arc of an umbrella, a soaked cuff, a whispered word he could no longer recall.

That was the weight he hadn't yet burned.

2

The nutrition-paste packet was empty.

David turned the foil bag over and scraped the last smear into his mouth with his index finger. The flavour was something between sweet and salty, as if two things that didn't belong together had been kneaded into one. Three years of eating it, and he still hadn't adjusted.

On the wall hung a diploma, its edges gone pale from years of red sand. The gold lettering was still legible: a top global university, an honours degree in physics. The date was seven years ago. That year David was twenty-four, his vision was 1.5, and he believed the universe was a string of code that could be completely calculated.

Now he looked at that diploma and found he had to squint to keep the double image from getting worse. The frame shook separately in left eye and right, like two leaves about to separate.

Footsteps from next door. Very light, dragging a heaviness that moved with them.

Emily pushed the door open and stood in the shadow. She was thin as a plant stripped of its roots; the oxygen mask pressed into her face had left dark-red marks in the skin. She dragged the old oxygen generator behind her, its wheels making a creaking sound on the floor.

"Dad, the medicine's gone."

Her voice was thin, as if coming from somewhere very far away.

David stood and crossed to her. He closed one eye, forcing his gaze to focus on his daughter's face—an act that demanded his full attention every time. He found Emily's hand. Cold. The fingertips had a faint tinge of purple.

"I'll go get some tomorrow," he said.

"They said our quota's used up." Emily looked down at the floor. "Last month, Uncle Liu's kid, after their quota ran out—"

She didn't finish.

David pulled her into his arms. The oxygen generator went on making its creaking sound, like a clock that refused to stop.

In this world ruled by the Zero Bureau, people like them were called "negative assets." Earth's resources could sustain only one-tenth of its population; the remaining nine-tenths waited in the underground slum called the Cradle for ship tickets that would never come.

David looked at the wall behind his daughter. A small line he had traced there—Emily's name written by herself at age three, crooked as an animal just learning to stand.

He remembered the expression on Anna's face the first time she saw that writing.

Then he realised he could no longer recall the details of that expression.

3

4:17 a.m.

David was not asleep. He lay on the mouldy sofa and listened to the sandstorm gradually die. The fine tapping sound slowly weakened, until only the occasional sigh from the ventilation pipe remained.

4:18 a.m.

The oxygen generator sighed.

4:19 a.m.

Then he heard another sound.

The hydraulic hatch being forced open—a dull thud, as if someone had jabbed a giant key into a lock. The walls of the entire bunker shook once.

David sat up and felt for his glasses.

Footsteps from the end of the corridor. Two pairs, heavy, regular, as if trained together.

The door was pushed open.

Two men in white full-isolation protective gear stood in the doorway. Their suits were spotless, blinding white in the dim emergency lights. On their chests: the Zero Bureau emblem—a circle with a line through it.

The lead man walked in. His gaze swept across the diploma on the wall, across the empty nutrition-paste wrapper on the table, and settled on David's face.

"David Keller," he said.

His voice held no temperature. Not cold—coldness is at least an attitude. His voice was a machine reading a document aloud, every word at exactly the same pitch.

"I don't have the data you want," David said.

The man didn't answer. He took a holographic projector from inside his suit and set it on the table. The light screen unfolded; a spinning black sphere appeared in midair.

The singularity.

"Our probes can't enter it," the man said. "Every AI with perfect logic crashes the moment it gets close. Not a malfunction—a crash. They can't process what they can't understand."

He took one step closer and stared through his visor at David.

"But you're different."

David said nothing.

"Your brain is a broken hard drive." The man's tone didn't change. "Your strabismus lets you see things that don't exist. Your memory prevents you from forgetting the way normal people do. You're an error. But the Zero Bureau needs this error."

The light screen changed, showing another image: a domed city on Mars, simulated sunlight on the streets, children running.

"A first-class ticket," the man said. "Your daughter gets the best medical care, real air, real sunlight. She'll grow up there."

David looked at that screen.

Children running. No oxygen masks on their faces.

"What's the price?" he asked.

"You'll die."

The man said those two words with the same tone one might use for: the weather's nice today.

"Not a metaphor. When you enter the singularity you'll be completely dismantled by Consistency Calibration. Your memories, your emotions, everything about you that we can't calculate—it will be removed. You'll become a perfect, logically consistent person."

He paused.

"But you won't be you anymore."

David stared at the spinning black sphere.

He thought of Anna. He thought of the way she evaporated in the flames. He thought of waking up afterward and finding his right eye could no longer focus. He thought of the doctors saying he would live forever in double vision—and the strange, almost liberating feeling in his chest—

Because it meant he never had to try to see this world without her clearly again.

"If I agree," David said, "when?"

"Now." The man turned and walked toward the door. "You have three minutes to pack."

4

Two minutes, forty-seven seconds.

David stood by Emily's bed. She was asleep; the oxygen generator's sighs covered her breathing. Her face looked even paler in the dimness; under the oxygen mask, a small patch of skin had broken down from long-term pressure.

He reached out to touch her hair.

Then he stopped.

He was afraid of waking her.

He didn't know what to say. If she woke up, how would he tell her? Tell her that Dad was going somewhere that would turn him into another person—someone who might not recognise her?

Or say nothing, let her wake up tomorrow morning to find him gone, with only a note that said Dad will be back soon—like all the parents who never came back?

Two minutes, fifty-nine seconds.

Footsteps from the end of the corridor.

David bent down, very gently, and pressed his lips to Emily's forehead. Her skin was cold. He didn't linger more than a second.

Then he stood up, walked out the door, and didn't look back.

5

The ship's launch shaft was on the surface.

When David stepped out of the elevator, the red sandstorm had just died. The sky was a colour between orange and grey, like cloth beginning to rot. At the horizon, the sun was rising—a dark-red disc obscured by dust, like looking at a lamp through blood.

The Icarus stood before him.

A slender ship, all black, without a single porthole. From a distance, it looked like a needle stuck in the ground.

David walked toward the boarding hatch. Wind snapped at his coat.

A woman stood at the hatch. She wore the Zero Bureau's white protective gear, but her visor was open. Her face was young—mid-twenties—and there was something in her eyes David hadn't seen in a long time: the light of someone alive.

"Mr. Keller," she said. "My name is Su Qing. I'll be monitoring your neural data."

Her voice was nothing like the man's—nothing like being drained of warmth. It was almost soft.

"There's something you need to know," she said. "From the moment we launch, you'll begin losing your memories. This isn't a side effect; it's the fuel. The ship's engine runs on emotional mass. Every memory you burn becomes the force that drives us forward."

She met his eyes.

"You can choose the order in which you burn them. Some people choose the most painful ones first. Some choose the most precious. There's no right answer."

David nodded.

He turned and looked back the way he had come. Nothing there—only dark-red wasteland and a horizon swallowed by dust.

Under that wasteland, an eight-year-old girl was sleeping. Her oxygen generator would sigh forty minutes from now, and she would wake in an empty room to find a piece of paper on the table.

One line on the paper:

"Dad's gone to find you the sun."

He would burn every memory of this farewell before the girl woke.

Not because it was painful.

Because only by forgetting her could he walk far enough.

David turned around and walked into the Icarus's hatchway.

Behind him, the dark-red sun rose on the horizon. Like an eye that refused to close.
